SIMPLE: shack
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shack
<hw>Shack</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Prov. E., to shake,
to shed. See <er>Shake</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To shed or fall, as
corn or grain at harvest.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Grose.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To feed in stubble, or upon waste corn.</def>
<mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To wander as a vagabond or a tramp.</def>
<mark>[Prev.Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shack</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shack
<hw>Shack</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Shack</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos>]</ety> <def>a small simple dwelling, usually having only one
room and of flimsy construction; a hut; a shanty; a cabin.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark></p>

<p><ent>Shack</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Shack
<hw>Shack</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Scot. <ets>shag</ets> refuse of
barley or oats.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The grain left after harvest or
gleaning; also, nuts which have fallen to the ground.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Liberty of winter pasturage.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A shiftless fellow; a low, itinerant beggar; a
vagabond; a tramp.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng. & Colloq. U.S.]</mark>
<rj><au>Forby.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the poor old <qex>shacks</qex> about the town found a friend
in Deacon Marble.</q> <rj><qau>H. W. Beecher.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These miserable <qex>shacks</qex> are so low that their occupants
cannot stand erect.</q> <rj><qau>D. C. Worcester.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Common of shack</b></col> <fld>(Eng.Law)</fld>, <cd>the
right of persons occupying lands lying together in the same common field
to turn out their cattle to range in it after harvest.</cd>
<rj><au>Cowell.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shackatory</ent>⟦br⟧
